Cheers

Software Development
Software Developers design and create the products that all of our customers use at every level of patient care. They are involved in every stage of the development process from creating complex algorithms to designing user interfaces and building sophisticated analytics tools, just to name a few. Software Developer is a role that involves creative problem solving and intense concentration. A very high technical aptitude is needed, as are advanced mathematical reasoning skills. Most of the work that Software Developers do is technical, though they are also involved in regular internal meetings and are required to go on a minimum of three customer trips per year. These trips provide developers with a deeper, more robust understanding of the end users' perspective. They also provide an opportunity to gather valuable feedback from our users. 

Technical Problem Solver
Technical Problem Solving provides meaningful opportunities to take ownership of challenging technical projects and make a difference at some of the nation’s most respected healthcare providers. Technical Problem Solvers work directly with our customers’ IT directors and project teams to build strong relationships while providing sound technical guidance. Working with their customers to optimize their use of Epic, Technical Problem Solvers are able to impact patient care in a positive way. What makes this role "fun" is the opportunity to solve problems that others couldn't figure out. They manage both technical challenges and customer relationships. As they work with customers, they'll troubleshoot programming issues, project plan for future upgrades, and interact with a large number of internal staff. The role offers a ton of variety and the opportunity to grow in many different directions. Technical Problem Solvers are known as the "jacks-of-all-trades" at Epic. On average, they spend 50% of their time on technical projects, such as using utilities, solving technical problems, debugging, programming fixes and enhancements. The other 50% of their time is spent on people-related work, such as customer calls, discussions, meetings, asking experts, etc. 

Quality Assurance
The Quality Assurance team tests our software from an end-user point of view to make sure that is of the highest quality possible before being sent out to customers. QAers catch and fix bugs, suggest enhancements, design creative tests plans, and work with the developers to fix any errors they find. The QA job helps all of our customers, end users, and patients because it ensures we are sending out a product that is going to work efficiently and accurately, thus improving patient care and the patient experience. This role takes majors of all backgrounds, and no prior software or technical knowledge is necessary. While the role does not require a technical background, we are looking for people who want to (and/or are proficient at) learning new and complicated things in a short period of time.

Technical Problem Solving provides meaningful opportunities to take ownership of challenging technical projects and make a difference at some of the nation’s most respected healthcare providers. Technical Problem Solvers work directly with our customers’ IT directors and project teams to build strong relationships while providing sound technical guidance. Working with their customers to optimize their use of Epic, Technical Problem Solvers are able to impact patient care in a positive way.What makes this role "fun" is the opportunity to solve problems that others couldn't figure out. They manage both technical challenges and customer relationships. As they work with customers, they'll troubleshoot programming issues, project plan for future upgrades, and interact with a large number of internal staff. The role offers a ton of variety and the opportunity to grow in many different directions.Technical Problem Solvers are known as the "jacks-of-all-trades" at Epic. On average, they spend 50% of their time on technical projects, such as using utilities, solving technical problems, debugging, programming fixes and enhancements. The other 50% of their time is spent on people-related work, such as customer calls, discussions, meetings, asking experts, etc.

Quality Assurance
The Quality Assurance team tests our software from an end-user point of view to make sure that is of the highest quality possible before being sent out to customers. QAers catch and fix bugs, suggest enhancements, design creative tests plans, and work with the developers to fix any errors they find. The QA job helps all of our customers, end users, and patients because it ensures we are sending out a product that is going to work efficiently and accurately, thus improving patient care and the patient experience. This role takes majors of all backgrounds, and no prior software or technical knowledge is necessary. While the role does not require a technical background, we are looking for people who want to (and/or are proficient at) learning new and complicated things in a short period of time.

The talk will be on Sunday, 9/20 at 2:00 PM in Glennan 321.  My plan is to skip over the basic syntax that was covered in the recitation, and spend the bulk of my time on explaining the differences between C and Java.  Some potential topics:

- Memory allocation vs garbage collection.
- Stack vs static vs heap variables, and how they're treated in C.
- Structs vs Java classes.
- Debugging C and segfaults with GDB.
- Compiling with a Makefile
- Effectively using man pages to understand how to use system calls.
